Social Engineering

1. Phishing attack
Phishing tricks users into revealing their credentials
Cybercriminals send fake emails or messages pretending to be trustworthy sources to trick victims into revealing passwords, credit card numbers, etc

2 Baiting
Attackers lure victims with a tempting offer (like a free USB drive infected with malware or fake download links) to compromise their systems
Offering something tempting (like free software) that contains malware

3. Pretexting
Attackers pretend to be someone trustworthy to extract data
A hacker creates a false scenario (“pretext”) to steal sensitive data (e.g., pretending to be IT support and asking for your login credentials).

4. Tailgating
Following an authorized person into a restricted area


